# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flet-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:flet-framework/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] The purpose of developing Material Design was to create a novel visual language, synthesizing the classic principles of good design with the innovation and potential of technology and science.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] Head designer Matías Duarte explained that "unlike real paper, our digital material expands and reforms intelligently.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] Material has physical surfaces and edges.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] Seams and shadows provide meaning about what you can touch." Material Design is based on paper-and-ink and skeuomorphic interaction concepts, but its implementation is more advanced.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] In 2021, Google revamped the design language, with the new language being titled Material You (Material Design 3).
[src:flet-framework/material-design] It provides more flexibility for designers to create custom themes with varying geometry, colors, and typography.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] In 2025, the next evolution of the design language, titled "Material 3 Expressive", was unveiled.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] Material Design has been gradually rolled out across Google's web and mobile products, providing a consistent experience across all platforms and applications.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] Google has also released application programming interfaces (APIs) for third-party developers to incorporate the design language into their applications.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] The canonical open source implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces is called Material Web.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] However, there are other official ways to do so, such as, for example, using Flutter or Jetpack Compose.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] After the 2018 revamp, Google began redesigning most of their apps based on an updated set of principles and guidelines dubbed "Material Design 2", which appeared on Android Pie.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] It provided a larger focus on customization of the basic Material Design components to adapt to the branding of the products in which it is being used.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] The updated guidelines further heavily emphasize white space, rounded corners, colorful icons, and bottom navigation bars.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] Google began utilizing a special size-optimized version of their proprietary Product Sans font called Google Sans.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] At Google I/O in May 2021, Google announced a new concept on Android 12 known as "Material You" (also known as "Material Design 3"), emphasizing increased animation, larger buttons, and the ability for custom UI themes to be generated from the user's wallpaper.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] Material You was gradually rolled out to various Google apps on older Android versions in the following months, and acted as a major focus on the Pixel 6 and Pixel 6 Pro smartphone series.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] At The Android Show: I/O Edition in May 2025, Google announced "Material 3 Expressive" for Android 16 and Wear OS 6.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] This version of Material Design shares similarities with its predecessor, and includes improved animations and a more colorful and fun design.
[src:flet-framework/material-design] It was gradually rolled out to Pixel phones (Pixel 6 and newer) and the Pixel Tablet, beginning in September 2025.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:flet-framework/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:flet-framework/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] A **single-page application** (**SPA**) is a web application or website that interacts with the user by dynamically rewriting the current web page with new data from the web server, instead of the default method of loading entire new pages.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] The goal is faster transitions that make the website feel more like a native app.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In a SPA, a page refresh never occurs; instead, all necessary HTML, JavaScript, and CSS code is either retrieved by the browser with a single page load, or the appropriate resources are dynamically loaded and added to the page as necessary, usually in response to user actions.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] The origins of the term *single-page application* are unclear, though the concept was discussed at least as early as 2003 by technology evangelists from Netscape.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Earlier forms were called rich web applications.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] JavaScript can be used in a web browser to display the user interface (UI), run application logic, and communicate with a web server.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Mature free libraries are available that support the building of a SPA, reducing the amount of JavaScript code developers have to write.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] There are various techniques available that enable the browser to retain a single page even when the application requires server communication.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] HTML authors can leverage element IDs to show or hide different sections of the HTML document.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Then, using CSS, authors can use the `:target` pseudo-class selector to only show the section of the page which the browser navigated to.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Web browser JavaScript frameworks and libraries, such as Angular, Ember.js, ExtJS, Knockout.js, Meteor.js, React, Vue.js, and Svelte have adopted SPA principles.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Aside from ExtJS, all of these are free.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] The following frameworks utilize WebAssembly or can build single-page applications (SPAs) with WebAssembly as a core technology or support mechanism.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] These frameworks enable high-performance and interactive client-side development, extending the SPA paradigm across languages and ecosystems.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] As of 2006, the most prominent technique used was Ajax.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Ajax involves using asynchronous requests to a server for XML or JSON data, such as with JavaScript's XMLHttpRequest or more modern `fetch()` (since 2017), or the deprecated ActiveX Object.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In contrast to the declarative approach of most SPA frameworks, with Ajax the website directly uses JavaScript or a JavaScript library such as jQuery to manipulate the DOM and edit HTML elements.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Ajax has further been popularized by libraries like jQuery, which provides a simpler syntax and normalizes Ajax behavior across different browsers which historically had varying behavior.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] WebSockets are a bidirectional real-time client-server communication technology that are part of the HTML specification.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] For real-time communication, their use is superior to Ajax in terms of performance and simplicity.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Server-sent events (SSEs) is a technique whereby servers can initiate data transmission to browser clients.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Once an initial connection has been established, an event stream remains open until closed by the client.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] SSEs are sent over traditional HTTP and have a variety of features that WebSockets lack by design such as automatic reconnection, event IDs, and the ability to send arbitrary events.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Although this method is outdated, asynchronous calls to the server may also be achieved using browser plug-in technologies such as Silverlight, Flash, or Java applets.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Requests to the server typically result in either raw data (e.g., XML or JSON), or new HTML being returned.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In the case where HTML is returned by the server, JavaScript on the client updates a partial area of the DOM (Document Object Model).
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] When raw data is returned, JavaScript on the client translates it into HTML using XSL or a JSON template before updating the DOM.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] A SPA moves logic from the server to the client, with the role of the web server evolving into a pure data API or web service.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This architectural shift has, in some circles, been coined "Thin Server Architecture" to highlight that complexity has been moved from the server to the client, with the argument that this ultimately reduces overall complexity of the system.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] The server keeps the necessary state in memory of the client state of the page.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In this way, when any request hits the server (usually user actions), the server sends the appropriate HTML and/or JavaScript with the concrete changes to bring the client to the new desired state (usually adding/deleting/updating a part of the client DOM).
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] At the same time, the state in server is updated.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Most of the logic is executed on the server, and HTML is usually also rendered on the server.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In some ways, the server simulates a web browser, receiving events and performing delta changes in server state which are automatically propagated to client.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This is a variant of the stateful server approach.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] The client page sends data representing its current state to the server, usually through Ajax requests.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This approach requires that more data be sent to the server and may require more computational resources per request to partially or fully reconstruct the client page state in the server.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] At the same time, this approach is more easily scalable because there is no per-client page data kept in the server and, therefore, Ajax requests can be dispatched to different server nodes with no need for session data sharing or server affinity.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Some SPAs may be executed from a local file using the file URI scheme.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This gives users the ability to download the SPA from a server and run the file from a local storage device, without depending on server connectivity.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] If such a SPA wants to store and update data, it must use browser-based Web Storage.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] These applications benefit from advances available with HTML.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Because the SPA is an evolution away from the stateless page-redraw model that browsers were originally designed for, some new challenges have emerged.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Because of the lack of JavaScript execution on crawlers of some popular Web search engines, SEO (search engine optimization) has historically presented a problem for public facing websites wishing to adopt the SPA model.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Between 2009 and 2015, Google Webmaster Central proposed and then recommended an "AJAX crawling scheme" using an initial exclamation mark in fragment identifiers for stateful AJAX pages (`#!`).
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Special behavior must be implemented by the SPA site to allow extraction of relevant metadata by the search engine's crawler.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] For search engines that do not support this URL hash scheme, the hashed URLs of the SPA remain invisible.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] These "hash-bang" URIs have been considered problematic by a number of writers including Jeni Tennison at the W3C because they make pages inaccessible to those who do not have JavaScript activated in their browser.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] They also break HTTP referer headers as browsers are not allowed to send the fragment identifier in the Referer header.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In 2015, Google deprecated their hash-bang AJAX crawling proposal.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Alternatively, applications may render the first page load on the server and subsequent page updates on the client.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This is traditionally difficult, because the rendering code might need to be written in a different language or framework on the server and in the client.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Using logic-less templates, cross-compiling from one language to another, or using the same language on the server and the client may help to increase the amount of code that can be shared.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In 2018, Google introduced dynamic rendering as another option for sites wishing to offer crawlers a non-JavaScript heavy version of a page for indexing purposes.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Dynamic rendering switches between a version of a page that is rendered client-side and a pre-rendered version for specific user agents.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This approach involves your web server detecting crawlers (via the user agent) and routing them to a renderer, from which they are then served a simpler version of HTML content.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] As of 2024, Google no longer recommends dynamic rendering, suggesting "server-side rendering, static rendering, or hydration" instead.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Because SEO compatibility is not trivial in SPAs, SPAs are commonly not used in a context where search engine indexing is either a requirement, or desirable.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Use cases include applications that surface private data hidden behind an authentication system.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In the cases where these applications are consumer products, often a classic "page redraw" model is used for the applications landing page and marketing site, which provides enough meta data for the application to appear as a hit in a search engine query.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Blogs, support forums, and other traditional page redraw artifacts often sit around the SPA that can seed search engines with relevant terms.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] As of 2021 and Google specifically, SEO compatibility for a plain SPA is straightforward and requires just a few simple conditions to be met.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] One way to increase the amount of code that can be shared between servers and clients is to use a logic-less template language like Mustache or Handlebars.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Such templates can be rendered from different host languages, such as Ruby on the server and JavaScript in the client.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] However, merely sharing templates typically requires duplication of business logic used to choose the correct templates and populate them with data.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Rendering from templates may have negative performance effects when only updating a small portion of the page—such as the value of a text input within a large template.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Replacing an entire template might also disturb a user's selection or cursor position, where updating only the changed value might not.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] To avoid these problems, applications can use UI data bindings or granular DOM manipulation to only update the appropriate parts of the page instead of re-rendering entire templates.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] With a SPA being, by definition, "a single page", the model breaks the browser's design for page history navigation using the "forward" or "back" buttons.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This presents a usability impediment when a user presses the back button, expecting the previous screen state within the SPA, but instead, the application's single page unloads and the previous page in the browser's history is presented.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] The traditional solution for SPAs has been to change the browser URL's hash fragment identifier in accord with the current screen state.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This can be achieved with JavaScript, and causes URL history events to be built up within the browser.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] As long as the SPA is capable of resurrecting the same screen state from information contained within the URL hash, the expected back-button behavior is retained.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] To further address this issue, the HTML specification has introduced pushState and replaceState providing programmatic access to the actual URL and browser history.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Analytics tools such as Google Analytics rely heavily upon entire new pages loading in the browser, initiated by a new page load.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] After the first page load, all subsequent page and content changes are handled internally by the application, which should simply call a function to update the analytics package.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Failing to call such a function, the browser never triggers a new page load, nothing gets added to the browser history, and the analytics package has no idea who is doing what on the site.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Similarly to the problems encountered with search engine crawlers, DAST tools may struggle with these JavaScript-rich applications.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Problems can include the lack of hypertext links, memory usage concerns and resources loaded by the SPA typically being made available by an Application Programming Interface or API.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Single-page applications are still subject to the same security risks as traditional web pages such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), but also a host of other unique vulnerabilities such as data exposure via API and client-side logic and client-side enforcement of server-side security.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In order to effectively scan a single-page application, a DAST scanner must be able to navigate the client-side application in a reliable and repeatable manner to allow discovery of all areas of the application and interception of all requests that the application sends to remote servers (e.g.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] It is possible to add page load events to a SPA using the HTML History API; this will help integrate analytics.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] The difficulty comes in managing this and ensuring that everything is being tracked accurately – this involves checking for missing reports and double entries.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Some frameworks provide free analytics integrations addressing most of the major analytics providers.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Developers can integrate them into the application and make sure that everything is working correctly, but there is no need to do everything from scratch.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] There are some ways of speeding up the initial load of a SPA, such as selective prerendering of the SPA landing/index page, caching and various code splitting techniques including lazy-loading modules when needed.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] But it's not possible to get away from the fact that it needs to download the framework, at least some of the application code; and will hit an API for data if the page is dynamic.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] This is a "pay me now, or pay me later" trade-off scenario.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] The question of performance and wait-times remains a decision that the developer must make.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] A SPA is fully loaded in the initial page load and then page regions are replaced or updated with new page fragments loaded from the server on demand.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] To avoid excessive downloading of unused features, a SPA will often progressively download more features as they become required, either small fragments of the page, or complete screen modules.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] In this way an analogy exists between "states" in a SPA and "pages" in a traditional website.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] Because "state navigation" in the same page is analogous to page navigation, in theory, any page-based web site could be converted to single-page replacing in the same page only the changed parts.
[src:flet-framework/single-page-application] The SPA approach on the web is similar to the single-document interface (SDI) presentation technique popular in native desktop applications.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:flet-framework/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
